 chapters explicitly examine the strategic limits and possibilities of the substantive equality rights approaches pursued by LEAF (The Women's Legal Education and Action Fund). Others focus on legal strategies mobilized in discreet areas of law and public policy by foreign domestic workers and racialized women, lesbians, women seeking reproductive freedom, women in the childcare movement, and anti-violence advocates. Recognizing the diversity of women across class, citizenship, race and ethnicity, sexual identity, culture, and (dis)ability, this collection evaluates the efficacy of the wide range of legal and political strategies women have employed, particularly in this post-Charter era. Women's Legal Strategies in Canada is the most comprehensive account of these important issues and will surely become the standard work in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aActions and defenseszCanada. 0aFeminist jurisprudencezCanada. 0aWomen's rightszCanada. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh1 aBakan, Abigail B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGotell, Lise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJhappan, Radha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJhappan, Radha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMajury, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Sheilah L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMclntyre, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Susan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSt Lewis, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStasiulis, Daiva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat